ntities.
    By discourse entity we mean a class of coreferent noun phrases.
    For each occurrence of a discourse entity in the text, the corresponding grid cell contains information about its grammatical role in the given sentence.
    Each grid column thus corresponds to a string from a set of categories reflecting the entity&#8217;s presence or absence in a sequence of sentences.
    Our set consists of four symbols: S (subject), O (object), X (neither subject nor object) and &#8211; (gap which signals the entity&#8217;s absence from a given sentence).
    Table 1 illustrates a fragment of an entity grid constructed for the text in Table 2.
    Since the text contains six sentences, the grid columns are of length six.
    Consider for instance the grid column for the entity trial, [O &#8211; &#8211; &#8211; &#8211; X].
    It records that trial is present in sentences 1 and 6 (as O and X respectively) but is absent from the rest of the sentences. cluster coreferent discourse entities is an important prer